garbo man – (manually) garbage-collected memory management

DISCLAIMER:
THIS IS A HOBBY PROJECT AND THUS NOT INTENDED FOR PRODUCTION USE.
IT IS INTENTIONALLY NOT THREAD SAFE.

Tracks allocations in a stack of allocation frames.
Each allocation frame is in turn represented as a stack holding all the allocations it is responsible for.
A new allocation frame may be requested by calling `void garbo_track(void)`.
A new allocation may be requested onto the current allocation frame (the one created by the last call to garbo_track) by calling `void* garbo_alloc(size_t bytes)`.
Allocations may only be freed in bulk through dropping the entire current allocation frame by calling `void garbo_free(void)`.

Example:

// header-only lib – request to also include implementation by defining the following symbol before inclusion
#define GARBOMAN_IMPL
#include "garboman.h"

int main() {
	// push first allocation frame
	garbo_track();
	// allocate and track some long-lived stuff on first allocation frame
	... = garbo_alloc(sizeof(...));

	// push, use and free a second allocation frame for shorter-lived allocations
	garbo_track();
	... = garbo_alloc(sizeof(...));
	do_some_short_lived_calculation(...);
	garbo_free();

	// continue working on first allocation frame
	... = garbo_alloc(sizeof(...));
	do_stuff(...);
	garbo_free();

	// no allocation frames remain
	return 0;
}

Garboman maintains a global variable `ref_stack` in the process' memory space pointing to the stack of allocation frames. 
Internally, both the reference stack and each allocation frame's allocation stack are implemented via lightweight append-only lists without capacity limits.
Any failure in garboman's internal routines causes instant termination of the program via `exit(EXIT_FAILURE)` since memory integrity cannot be guarateed anymore.
The lib's name is taken from the Australian slang word "garbo" short for "garbage man".

